post_cb({"28778747": {"ParentId": "28778706", "CommentCount": "2", "Body": "<p>Absolutely not. From the C++14 working draft (chosen here because I was able to find it easily, not because it's specific to C++14):</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_28778706_28778747_0\">A prvalue of type <code>bool</code> can be converted to a prvalue of type <code>int</code>, with <code>false</code> becoming zero and <code>true</code> becoming one.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>\u2014 <a href=\"http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2014/n4296.pdf\" rel=\"noreferrer\">http://www.open-std.org/jtc1/sc22/wg21/docs/papers/2014/n4296.pdf</a> \u00a74.5.6 (page 85)</p>\n<p>Indeed, this behavior is common to most programming languages. Off the top of my head, for instance, Perl, Python, PHP, and Javascript all treat 0 as false and nonzero values as true. The only situation I can think of where 0 is \"true\" is in UNIX shell scripting, where an exit code of 0 is used for success and nonzero values are used for errors.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "149341", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "28778747", "Score": "5", "CreationDate": "2015-02-28T06:07:08.590", "LastActivityDate": "2015-02-28T06:07:08.590"}, "28778706": {"CommentCount": "5", "AcceptedAnswerId": "28778747", "ClosedDate": "2015-03-06T22:16:03.060", "CreationDate": "2015-02-28T06:01:28.927", "LastActivityDate": "2015-02-28T06:07:08.590", "PostTypeId": "1", "ViewCount": "2355", "Title": "Does boolean true ever return 0?", "Id": "28778706", "Score": "1", "Body": "<p>I was in a lecture and on the power point slides states that true would return 0 and false would return 1. I stated that in Visual Studio anything non zero is considered true, but is there a C++ standard that defines 0 as true?</p>\n<p>Visual studio's results were disregarded as non standard but I doubt that it is.</p>\n<pre><code>bool tru = true; // returns 0\nbool fal = false; // returns 1\n</code></pre>\n", "Tags": "<c++>", "OwnerUserId": "2084219", "AnswerCount": "2"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_28778706_28778747_0": {"section_id": 26, "quality": 1.0, "length": 14}, "so_28778706_28778744_0": {"section_id": 33, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}, "n3337": {"so_28778706_28778747_0": {"section_id": 23, "quality": 1.0, "length": 14}, "so_28778706_28778744_0": {"section_id": 30, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}}, "n4659": {"so_28778706_28778744_0": {"section_id": 33, "quality": 0.9166666666666666, "length": 11}, "so_28778706_28778747_0": {"section_id": 26, "quality": 1.0, "length": 14}}}, "28778744": {"ParentId": "28778706", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "0", "CreationDate": "2015-02-28T06:06:32.567", "Score": "2", "LastEditorUserId": "-1", "LastEditDate": "2017-05-23T12:08:08.997", "Id": "28778744", "OwnerUserId": "3425536", "Body": "<p>As mentioned in the accepted answer <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/a/2725063/3425536\">here</a>, <code>true</code> is defined by the standard to compare equal to <code>1</code>, and <code>false</code> to <code>0</code>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_28778706_28778744_0\">(\u00a74.7/4): \"If the source type is bool, the value false is converted to zero and the value true is converted to one.\"</p>\n</blockquote>\n", "LastActivityDate": "2015-02-28T06:06:32.567"}});